## Plus: user refinement to pattern 1 (bounded-iteration model)

The doc currently says "round-3 REQUEST-CHANGES → RECOMMEND-REVERT." User clarifies the model is more nuanced:

> Round 3 is **revert vs role-flip based on whether progress is being made**. If the brief itself is architecturally wrong (progress stalled), revert. If progress is real but iteration is converging slowly, **flip the roles**: reviewer agent becomes the developer; developing agent becomes the reviewer. Fresh eyes on the same problem from a different vantage point.

The two existing reverts (ajv migration, Phase 6 first attempt) are examples of **progress-stalled** round-3 outcomes — role-flip would have been wrong for both because the bugs were in the briefs, not the developer execution.

**Fix:** Expand pattern 1 to cover both round-3 outcomes (revert when stalled, role-flip when progressing). State the decision criteria explicitly. Note that role-flip preserves accumulated context: the original developer brings architectural context from their attempts; the original reviewer has seen the iteration arc and knows where fixes failed.

